#X text 71 665 About detuning \, note that it can be done in two ways \, logarithmically or linearly. In the previous example and above to the left we have a fixed detuning value in Hz. This means that this frequency difference is fixed for all notes. Another way is to slightly detune in cents \, directly in the MIDI input value. The other example to the right detunes by o1 cent by adding '0.01' to the MIDI value \, where the frequency difference depends on the MIDI pitch., f 69;
#X text 39 50 When combining different oscillators \, detuning is a nice technique to design rich and evolving timbres because all the beating partials. When triggering repeated notes in this case you can have each one sounding a bit different if you keep the oscillators "free running" \, as they keep shifting the phase relationships. Such an effect can be desriable or not and one way to prevent this from happening is syncing the oscillators at each Note On event. Both [mono] and [mono~] have a rightmost outlet for note-on triggering and retriggering. In the case of [mono] we have a bang output and in [mono~] we have an impulse output., f 72;
